{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"a92654b5-aaaf-4e93-966d-e04e1e8e8287","content":"Use `dotnet watch test` — it watches for file changes and automatically re-runs your tests:\n\n```\ndotnet watch test --filter \"RemoveStock_ExceedsAvailable_ThrowsException\"\n```\n\nThe `--filter` flag limits it to just your failing test for faster feedback. When you save a change to `InventoryServiceTests.cs`, the test re-runs automatically.\n\n**Quick hint on the bug:** `RemoveStock` subtracts without checking if enough stock exists — it never throws. You'll need to add a guard like:\n\n```csharp\npublic void RemoveStock(string sku, int quantity)\n{\n    var current = _stock.GetValueOrDefault(sku);\n    if (quantity > current)\n        throw new InvalidOperationException(\"Insufficient stock\");\n    _stock[sku] = current - quantity;\n}\n```\n\nWant me to apply that fix and start the watcher?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"53c34953-f928-4b13-acf2-136e66446511","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user wants to set up hot reload for their test project. Since this is using .NET 10 with Microsoft.Testing.Platform (as specified in global.json), I can use `dotnet test --hotreload` or `dotnet watch test` to enable hot reload.\n\nLet me check which approach works best. With .NET 10 and Microsoft.Testing.Platform, `dotnet test --hotreload` is available. But `dotnet watch test` is the more traditional approach.\n\nActually, with the Microsoft.Testing.Platform runner configured in global.json, the recommended approach for .NET 10 is to use `dotnet test --hotreload`. But let me verify if this is available.\n\n\n`dotnet watch test` is the standard way to go—it watches for file changes and automatically reruns the tests whenever I save changes.","outputTokens":442,"requestId":"A842:13E67C:274832E:29BD753:6A0493BA"},"id":"68765175-655d-486d-9a22-e9114192baaf","timestamp":"2026-05-13T15:07:49.165Z","parentId":"637e09f1-4549-4e40-a226-411e29b0ee07"}
